# Cheat Sheet

## Opening Dired

* SPC f d — Find directory with Dired.
* SPC . — Find or create file (navigating to a folder opens Dired).
* C-x d — Standard Emacs shortcut to open Dired.
* q — Quit / exit Dired buffer. [1, 2, 4, 5]

## Navigation

* j / k — Move down and up through items (Vim motion).
* RET — Open selected file or step into a directory.
* - / ^ — Go up one level to the parent directory.
* ( — Toggle simple view (hides file sizes, permissions, and owners).
* O — Toggle sorting order between file name and modification date. [1, 2, 5, 6, 7]

## Marking Files (Batch Actions)

* m — Mark file or folder.
* u — Unmark current file or folder.
* U — Clear all marks in the buffer.
* t — Invert the current selections.
* * / — Select all directories.
* % m — Mark files matching a specific regular expression. [1, 2, 8]

## File Operations

* + — Create a new directory.
* SPC f f - Create a new file
* C — Copy marked files (copies to the other window if split).
* R — Move or rename marked files.
* d — Flag a file for deletion (adds a D marker).
* x — Execute deletion for all flagged files.
* M — Change file permissions (chmod). [1, 2, 9]

## Inline Mass Renaming (Writable Dired)

* C-c C-e / i — Convert Dired into an editable buffer. Use standard text editing commands to change file names or paths instantly.
* C-c C-c or :w — Commit changes to the file system.
* C-c ESC — Cancel edits without changes. [1, 2, 4, 10]
